<rating>1</rating><Text>During the year of 2017 I was planning to enter the PMP exam but could not even schedule it due to the usual busy schedule at work (the real reason being not assigning the needed priority to this matter). Then at the end of December 2017 I heard the exam contents changes to PMBOK6 in March 2018 but again it was only at the end of January 2018 when I became PMI member and scheduled the exam for March 20, 2018 (the latest free slot that I could find for my location).
I spent the whole February to complete only the thorough reading of PMBOK5, spending on average 2 hours per day (4 hours on weekends) since I continued to go to office. Then in March 2018 I decided to take 2 weeks off to have full dedication for studying Rita's Book supported by free exam simulators and Cornelius Fichtner videos from OSP International, a pocket exam book of Rita, some exam questions from previous trainings (I had attended one formal 36-hour PMP prep course back in December 2014 outside office and an additional one in 2017 at office, both based on PMBOK5) During the last two weeks I studied 8-10 hours per day on average. Besides, I have worked in project and program management in 2014-2017 period. During the preparation for the exam in the moments when I felt I would not make it due to shortage of time to prepare properly for the exam, the two advices that I liked most were 1) Do not over study! 2) Not all of the questions at the exam will be that difficult. I did not run any mock exam with more than 20 questions at a time. Since I heard a lot of warnings that many run out of time during the exam, my strategy at the exam was to quickly pass and answer ALL the questions by marking the ones that I was not sure about. I marked some 25-30 and had couple of questions not answered at all but at the second pass I changed my mind only on two of the marked ones and answered the remaining two. With this much effort and practical work background plus headphones (for full focus) and a single short call-of-the-nature break I was able to pass the exam in my first attempt.</Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><resp>{'time': 1530884634252, 'text': 'Congratulations on passing the exam on such a tight schedule, Erg√ºn. My Favorites<//user_name>
<userid>114488391518618406563< /userid><pics>None<//pics><text>First of all, thank you, Cornelius for your outstanding work on the PrepCast series.  The series was my first set of material used in my PMP exam prep journey. I passed the exam, thanks to the concise yet comprehensive material.  Although it is recommended by most to read the PMBOK guide cover to cover several times, I had skimmed it only once. I tried reading it a second time but found that it took too long.  I resorted to using the copious notes I had taken while listening to your podcasts.  That worked for me.  Along with another study guide,  I was confident enough to pass the exam.

I do have a couple of suggestions:

1 - While I know that the questions in the PMP exam is different for everyone, mine felt like most of the questions had more than one "very good" answer.  It was stressful throughout the exam trying to pick the best one.  My experience with the PrepCast mock exams were a little different in that most of the answer choices were clear that there is only one good answer.  As such, I was able to finish the mock exams within 3 hours every time and score well.  On the real exam, I took the 4 entire hours and could have used a few more minutes to review the marked questions.  The suggestion here would be to incorporate multiple good answers in your questions to better mimic the real exam.

2 - On your calculation questions, it would be good if the bar chart (introduction to the question) is different in every mock exam.  I found that every time I see the same bar chart, I'm "cheating" when I get the question correct because I had seen the chart before and did not need to read the details more carefully.

Thanks once again!<//text>< Rate>
5</Rate>

The Agile PrepCast was an excellent beginning to my studies for the PMI-ACP Exam. I found the content to be well organized and clearly presented, with plenty of real-world examples. I appreciated the opportunity to gain not only the required contact hours of training, but the 37 PDUs I earned were a huge bonus that enabled me to renew my PMP certification early!

I scored 75% after completing the course, then studied from the Mike Griffiths PMI-ACP Exam Prep book and workbook to expand my understanding. <userid>116088476747815559876<//userid>< Name>
Angela Liu<//Name>
<Date>1514901722177</Date><Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
I used the PrepCast (PMBOK 5th Ed) and a few books to study for my PMP exam, which I passed on the first try. The formula guide that accompanied the PrepCast was very helpful. The lectures, however, contain a lot of repetitive contents (overview of the knowledge area and process groups) and I didn't finished all of the lectures. I took several practice exams using the simulator. The simulator gives a realistic feel of the exam experience. However, some of the practice exam questions on ITTOs are a bit too stringent and I disagree with some of the answers. When I looked up those questions on the 6th Ed of the PMBOK guide, I found that my answers to those questions would be correct based on the updated PMBOK guide, which has more comprehensive and logical ITTOs. Based on my exam experience, the ITTOs asked on the exam can be answered by common sense. The PrepCast discussion forum is excellent. I have found a lot of like-minded students and the discussions are very helpful, as I don't have a local study group. Overall, I think PrepCast is a solid exam preparation product, but I would advise the students to think more broadly on the sample ITTO questions.<//text>
<pics>None< /pics><resp>{'time': 1517255542011, 'text': 'Thank you for this comprehensive feedback Angela. We have already addressed two of your critique points: In our new PrepCast Sixth edition we have removed much of the repetition that you have seen. (This also bothered me, so I took action to remove it). And as far as the ITTO questions go, we are reviewing and rewriting every single one of our simulator questions based on the new requirements, style and type of questions on the actual exam. This means that almost all ITTO questions are disappearing. Some will remain but the questions themselves are more situational than knowledge based. In this way new students will not feel the repetitiveness nor have as many ITTO questions.'}</resp><Gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<user>112075248654908393557</user><username>Josiah Seale<//username>< Date>
1505961206833<//Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate><Text>Pros:

The PMP certification addresses extremely useful content, but in most cases learning it can be challenging. It's not because the material is complicated, but rather human nature. Let's be honest: learning best practices for putting together e.g. a schedule management plan can make for dry material at best.

Enter Cornelius Fichtner. With an enthusiasm that defies belief, he lays out the material in a thoughtfully logical sequence and pays attention to providing just the right amount of content. It's enough to make the material understandable and retainable without delving too far into the weeds. He explains why the pieces of information he is explaining are important,  and how they connect to the other topics already discussed.

The course is a lot of hours of video (which is also required for it to qualify with PMI) so it requires some determination to get through it, but figuring out I could use ear buds to take my computer to my favorite hookah cafe to sit down with Digital Cornelius was sufficient to (eventually) get me through all of the videos, typically in stints of 2-3 hours at a time.

After completing the PM PrepCast course I comfortably passed the test with highest marks in all sections. Many of the project management experience hours described on my PMI application were with a teensy startup that had run out of money, so I was "randomly selected" for an audit, but it was all verifiably true and PMI was happy with the PM PrepCast as the course I took, so I am now a certified PMP. As a side benefit, after 15-20 hookah cafe stints with Digital Cornelius in 2-3 hour stretches, even a year later I can still pull off a killer Cornelius Fichtner impression to impress all my friends and guests at parties.

A final nice thing about the PM Prepcast is the ability to download the videos -- they are well-organized and succinct, so I put them on a work computer to have them at my fingertips in case I ever need a refresher on some of the finer points. 8/10, would repeat (if I really really had to)

Cons:
For awhile Cornelius's chipper Swiss voice haunted my dreams, happily chattering about earned value management and procurement performance reviews as the soundtrack to a gigantic battle between Godzilla and Biollante, except one of them was actually a Schedule Performance Index and the other was a Cost Performance Index. I got over it though.< /Text>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
< resp>
None< /resp>

<text>It took me a lot of time to decide if I want to go for classroom training or online training. Lot of my friends had suggested classroom but I was not comfortable with attending 4 day classes over two weekends. So I decided to go for online training.
Before deciding on pm prepcast I did a lot of research on different online providers. I was looking for good quality videos and good support. After reviewing and reading loads of user comments I finally decided on pm prepcast and it turned out to be a very good decision. Not only the quality of the videos is very good but if you have read Pmbok or any other book (I read Rita) before watching the videos you can very easily relate to the material. The way the content is covered is easy to understand as the video durations are not very long. So you can do one or two in one sitting and not get overwhelmed. I used to do two in mornings and one in evening so it work d out for me.
The other thing I really liked is then way Cornelius has explained how to prepare for the exam and about the application process. It was really very helpful for me as I did not have any other support while preparing. I studied alone and took about 10 weeks to finish the exam. Though I had read pmbok and Rita earlier but it was only after going through the videos that I got confident about the material.
The support is just amazing. I used to post questions and used to get reply very quickly. Thanks for that.
Overall I am very happy that I opted or pm prepcast and cleared the exam in first attempt. Now I have already started to plan for maintaining the certification and I currently reviewing the pdus offered by pm prepcast.
I want to thank Cornelius and whole pm prep cast team.

<Review>I was using the project management prepcast PMP simulator about 2 years ago to prepare for my PMP exam. I tried a few free simulators back then, but liked the prepcast the most. Their simulator has a very nice user interface, and it does not require a download. So you can use it from any place and on any device. Well, I did not test on all of course, but it worked on my Windows laptop and iPhone. Very convenient. The questions in the simulator are comparable with what I eventually encountered on my real PMP exam. But the main feature which I really liked and what I did not see from any other companies, is their live feedback. For example, if you need a clarification on a specific question or you just disagree with the correct answer, you can click the live feedback button right on the screen of that question, and one of their PMP guys gets back to you with a detailed explanation of why the correct answer is really correct. Well, sometimes they were wrong, and I even succeeded to convince them to change some of their questions, which I guess was very helpful for them, but also helped me to gain my confidence in my knowledge. This communication back and forth was highly valuable and helped me a lot. It's like having your own PMP coach for free. Well done, prepcast! I would definitely recommend this product to anyone who is preparing for their PMP exam. Well worth the money and really prepares you for THE day!</Review><user_name>staspo< /user_name>< gmap_id>
